President Barack Obama has proclaimed October 15, 2014, as Blind Americans Equality Day. This day is dedicated to honoring the contributions of blind and visually impaired Americans. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of equal access, equal opportunity, and equal respect for all individuals. It highlights the achievements and abilities of blind Americans in various fields, such as education, art, and employment. The administration is committed to expanding opportunities for individuals with disabilities and promoting accessibility. The proclamation also mentions the significance of Braille instruction in classrooms and the protection against disability-based discrimination. The Affordable Care Act is mentioned as a measure to prevent health insurance companies from denying coverage based on pre-existing conditions or disabilities. The proclamation encourages public officials, business and community leaders, educators, librarians, and all Americans to observe this day with appropriate ceremonies and activities.